  Results (BenchmarkAdaptiveEncode, 5s, Ryzen 7 2700X, 56.66 MB/s encode):
    83.8% cum — gatherRans6 (per-ratio ε decision loop)
      42.6% cum —   DequantizeRatio → math.Pow (Exp+Pow for dequantize)
      31.4% cum —   QuantizeRatio → math.Log (log-space mapping)
      23.5% flat —  math.archLog (Log itself — transcendental, unavoidable)
      17.6% flat —  math.archExp (Exp inside Pow — transcendental, unavoidable)
     5.3% cum — writeRansBody6 + RansEncode6 (rANS encode — near-free)
     1.7% cum — RansCountFreqs6 + buildRansTables6 (table build — negligible)

  Key finding: the bottleneck is QuantizeRatio+DequantizeRatio called TWICE
  per ClassNormal ratio in gatherRans6 (once to quantize, once to dequantize
  for error measurement). The transcendentals (Log/Exp/Pow) dominate.
  rANS table build is NOT the bottleneck — no tuning needed there.

  Optimisation opportunity (6e candidate):
    Eliminate the DequantizeRatio call in gatherRans6. The error can be
    computed from the quantized index directly without round-tripping through
    float64: err = |ratio - dequant| / ratio. But dequant requires Exp—
    we can instead bound error analytically from the bit-depth step size
    (delta = 2^(1/2^bits) - 1 for log-space quantization), making the
    per-ratio decision a single comparison with no Exp call.
    Estimated saving: ~40% of total encode time (eliminates one Exp+Pow per ratio).
